#Title: Predictive Modeling of Mouse Decision-Making Using Neural Spike Data

#Abstract:

This study leverages neural activity data from visual cortex recordings of mice to predict behavioral outcomes (feedback type) based on spike train patterns and stimulus contrasts. Utilizing data from a subset of experiments by Steinmetz et al. (2019), our analysis specifically investigates the association between neuronal spike activity during visual stimulus presentation and subsequent decision-making behaviors in mice. The project is separated into six parts, which of them are introduction, exploratory analysis, data integration, predictive modeling, prediction performance on the test sets, and discussion. The project uses many methods to analyze the data like plotting, normalization and then selects some models like decision trees and random forests to predict the outcome based on the features of the data.

#Section 1 Introduction

Understanding how neural activity translates into behavioral outcomes is fundamental in neuroscience. In a series of experiments conducted by Steinmetz et al. (2019), mice were presented with visual stimuli of varying contrasts and tasked with decision-making behaviors that resulted in either rewards or penalties. Neural activity in the visual cortex was simultaneously recorded, producing spike trains—temporal sequences of neuron firings.Our project aims to analyze spike train data from 18 sessions involving four different mice—Cori, Forssman, Hench, and Lederberg—to build predictive models capable of classifying the trial outcomes based solely on neural and visual stimulus data. Each trial’s feedback (success or failure) is associated with the contrasts presented (left and right stimuli) and neuronal activity, recorded as spike counts within specified time bins.By applying advanced statistical modeling techniques, including tree-based algorithms, our study seeks to elucidate the relationship between neuronal dynamics and behavioral decision-making. The outcomes of this study will offer insights into neural encoding and decoding processes and potentially inform future research in neural correlates of decision-making.

Section 2 Exploratory analysis

#2.1 Summarizing Table

# Load required libraries
library(dplyr)
## 
## 载入程序包：'dplyr'

##     filter, lag
## The following objects are masked from 'package:base':

##     intersect, setdiff, setequal, union
library(knitr)

# Define the folder path containing session files
folder_path <- "C:/Users/29707/OneDrive/Desktop/sessions"

# Initialize a list to store session data
session <- list()

# Loop through all 18 session files and load them
for (i in 1:18) {
  session[[i]] <- readRDS(paste0(folder_path, "/session", i, ".rds"))  # Corrected concatenation
}

# Process each session and extract relevant data
all_sessions <- bind_rows(
  lapply(1:18, function(i) {
    data <- session[[i]]
    
    # Compute summary statistics
    success_count <- sum(data$feedback_type == 1, na.rm = TRUE)
    failure_count <- sum(data$feedback_type == -1, na.rm = TRUE)
    mean_contrast_left <- mean(data$contrast_left, na.rm = TRUE)
    mean_contrast_right <- mean(data$contrast_right, na.rm = TRUE)

    # Ensure neuron count is derived correctly
    neuron_count <- if (is.list(data$spks) && length(data$spks) > 0) {
      nrow(data$spks[[1]])  # Use the first trial to determine neuron count
    } else {
      NA  # If no spikes available, set to NA
    }
    
    # Return a **single row per session**
    data.frame(
      session_id = i,  # Assign session number
      Mouse = unique(data$mouse_name),  
      Date = unique(data$date_exp),
      neuron_count = neuron_count,  
      trial_count = length(data$spks),  
      mean_contrast_left = mean_contrast_left,
      mean_contrast_right = mean_contrast_right,
      success_count = success_count,
      failure_count = failure_count,
      success_rate = success_count / (success_count + failure_count),
      mean_spikes = mean(unlist(data$spks), na.rm = TRUE),# Avoid dividing by zero
      Variance_SpikeRate=var(unlist(data$spks), na.rm = TRUE)
    )
  })
)

There are 18 sessions in total and each of them contains five variables for every trial. They are the type of feedback(1 for success and -1 for failure), contrast of the left stimulus, contrast of the right stimulus, centers of the time bins for spikes, numbers of spikes of neurons in the visual cortex and area of the brain where each neuron lives. The project builds a table to combine all the data together clearly. The table groups the data as session and summarizes some important data. It contains the mouse name, the number of neuron, the number of trials, the mean of the contrast for right and left stimuli, the success and failure count success rate and the mean spikes in each session. Since there are so many trials for spikes in each session so that calculating the mean spikes make it easier to analyze the change of the spikes in each session. The success rate, success and failure count, and the mean of contrast stimuli are to investigate the relationship between change of feedback and the contrast stimuli in each session. Obviously, there the range of the number of neuron is from 474 to 1769 and the range of the number of triasl is from 114 to 447, which indicate the data is large so that the trained predictive model is more accurate and the result is more convincing. What’s more, all of the success rate surpass the 0.5, which indicates the possibility of success rate is high and the mouse is making correct decisions in the visual task more frequently.

  session[[i]] <- readRDS(paste0(folder_path, "/session", i, ".rds"))  # Corrected concatenation

# Process each session and extract relevant data
all_sessions_spks<- bind_rows(
  lapply(1:18, function(i) {
    data <- session[[i]]

    # Return a **single row per session**
    data.frame(
      mean_spikes = data$spks
      
    )
  })
)



mean_spikes_per_trial <- sapply(all_sessions_spks, function(spk) {
    if (is.null(spk)) return(NA) # Avoid errors if missing data
    mean(unlist(spk), na.rm = TRUE)
})


if (length(mean_spikes_per_trial) > 0) {
    mean_spikes_df <- data.frame(
        Trial = seq_along(mean_spikes_per_trial),
        Mean_Spikes = mean_spikes_per_trial
    )
} else {
    print("Error: mean_spikes_per_trial is empty")
}


ggplot(mean_spikes_df, aes(x = Trial, y = Mean_Spikes)) +

In general, despite variability, there are consistent trends where higher mean neural activity tends to be accompanied by higher variance.

# Normalize data
df_pca_scaled <- scale(all_sessions%>% select_if(is.numeric))

# Perform PCA
pca_result <- prcomp(df_pca_scaled, center = TRUE, scale. = TRUE)

# Prepare PCA dataframe
pca_df <- data.frame(PC1 = pca_result$x[,1], PC2 = pca_result$x[,2], Session = all_sessions$session_id)

# Plot PCA
library(ggplot2)
ggplot(pca_df, aes(x = PC1, y = PC2, color = as.factor(Session))) +
  geom_point() +
  theme_minimal() +
  labs(title = "PCA: PC1 vs PC2", color = "Session")

The project scales and normalizes the mean and variance of spikes in each session, which centers and scales the data to unit variance and brings values between 0 and 1 to facilitate comparisons across sessions. Data normalization helps improve PCA performance and enhance clustering accuracy. Then the project extracts shared patterns across sessions using principal component analysis and correlation and clustering analysis. PCA is performed for reducing the dimensionality to capture shared patterns in neural activity across sessions and the projects visualizes how different sessions relate to each other based on the first two principal components (PC1 vs. PC2), which highlight dominant trends across sessions using a scatter plot. The sessions are spread across both PC1 and PC2, suggesting variability in neural activity across sessions.Some sessions appear grouped together, implying shared neural patterns.Sessions like 1, 2, and 4 are positioned close to each other, while 15, 16, and 17 also form another cluster.Sessions with larger distances between them indicate differences in mean spikes, variance, or other neural activity metrics.PCA successfully reduces the complexity of neural data while preserving the most important variations.

#3.2 Hierarchical Clustering

# Compute the distance matrix
dist_matrix <- dist(all_sessions$mean_spikes)

# Perform hierarchical clustering
hc <- hclust(dist_matrix, method = "ward.D2")

# Convert to dendrogram object
dend <- as.dendrogram(hc)

# Plot the dendrogram with improved readability
ggdendrogram(dend, rotate = TRUE, theme_dendro = FALSE) +
  ggtitle("Improved Cluster Dendrogram") +
  theme_minimal() +
  theme(axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 90, hjust = 1, size = 12),
        axis.text.y = element_text(size = 12),
        plot.title = element_text(hjust = 0.5, size = 14))

Hierarchical clustering is applied using Ward’s method grouping sessions based on spike activity similarity. The clustering structure is visualized with a dendrogram, showing how different sessions cluster together based on neural activity.Sessions are grouped into clusters based on their similarity. The leftmost branches represent sessions with the most similarity. The rightmost branches (longer distances) indicate more distinct sessions. The largest division occurs around the 0.03 mark on the y-axis, splitting the sessions into two major clusters. The rightmost group (including Session 3) is distinct from the rest, meaning it has different neural activity characteristics.Within the left cluster, sessions 17, 10, and 18 are grouped closely, indicating similar neural activity. Sessions 5, 16, and 14 form another subgroup. Sessions 1, 9, and 2 cluster together, showing shared patterns.Sessions within the same clusters share similar mean spikes, variance, or firing patterns. Larger separation (e.g., Session 3) suggests different experimental conditions or variations in neural activity.

# Define file path to .rds files
file_list <- list.files(path = "C:/Users/29707/OneDrive/Desktop/sessions", 
                        pattern = "*.rds", full.names = TRUE)

# Function to extract `spks` and add session ID
extract_spks <- function(file, session_id) {
  data <- readRDS(file)
  if ("spks" %in% names(data)) {
    df <- data.frame(spks =  mean(unlist(data$spk)))
    df$session_id <- session_id  # Assign session ID
    return(df)
  } else {
    return(NULL)  # Skip files without `spks`
  }
}



library(dplyr)

# Load session data
session_integration <- bind_rows(lapply(1:18, function(i) {
    data <- readRDS(paste0("C:/Users/29707/OneDrive/Desktop/sessions/session", i, ".rds"))
    
    if (is.null(data$spks) || length(data$spks) == 0) {
        return(NULL)  # Skip sessions with no spike data
    }
    
    trial_count <- length(data$spks)
    trial_data <- data.frame(
        session_id = rep(i, trial_count),
        contrast_left = data$contrast_left,
        contrast_right = data$contrast_right,
        feedback_type = data$feedback_type,
        spike_count = sapply(data$spks, length)
    )
    
    return(trial_data)
}), .id = "session")

The project addresses differences between sessions by distance metrics & clustering and creating a new table. A distance matrix is computed based on mean spike rates and Hierarchical clustering groups sessions with similar neural responses while identifying distinct outliers. In addition, the project creates a new table, which extracts spike train data and consolidate the neuron activity information across sessions. Mean spikes and variance of spike rates can be compared across sessions through the table and also the table consolidates trial-level features to observe session-specific variations in behavioral and neural data.

The project predicts the feedback type (Success or Failure) of a trial based on neural activity and stimulus contrast using a decision tree model. First, the project uses the table from data integration and combine them into a training dataset. Then the feedback type (Success or Failure) is converted into a factor variable to ensure the model treats the feedback as a classification problem. After that, the model is trained using the Recursive Partitioning and Regression Trees (rpart) method by three predictor variables, which of them are left-side stimulus contrast, right-side stimulus contrast and total number of spikes (neural activity measure). The optimal Model was chosen at cp = 0.0002715547, as it gave the highest accuracy (0.7019654 ). The accuracy is 0.7019654 which means the model correctly classifies ~71% of the trials. It is a reasonable performance for a simple decision tree. Kappa measures agreement beyond chance. If Kappa >0.75 is considered excellent so that Kappa=0.1681 suggests weak agreement beyond random chance.

#4.2 Train Random Forest Model

library(tidyverse)
library(caret)
library(randomForest)
library(e1071)  # For SVM
library(xgboost)
library(tidyverse)
library(rpart)          # Decision Tree
library(dplyr)
library(DMwR2)


set.seed(123)  # Ensure reproducibility

# Combine them into training data
train_data <- bind_rows(session_integration)
train_data$feedback_type <- factor(train_data$feedback_type, 
                                   levels = c(-1, 1), 
                                   labels = c("Fail", "Success"))
# Train Random Forest Model
# Normalize numerical features
preProc <- preProcess(train_data[, sapply(train_data, is.numeric)], method = c("center", "scale"))

# Apply scaling
train_scaled <- predict(preProc, train_data)


rf_model <- train(
  feedback_type ~ contrast_left + contrast_right + spike_count,
  data = train_data,
  method = "rf",  # Random Forest
  metric = "Accuracy"
)
## note: only 2 unique complexity parameters in default grid. Truncating the grid to 2 .
# Print model summary
print(rf_model)

#4.3 XGB MODEL

library(tidyverse)
library(caret)
library(randomForest)
library(e1071)  # For SVM
library(xgboost)
library(tidyverse)
library(rpart)          # Decision Tree
library(dplyr)
library(DMwR2)


# Combine them into training data
train_data <- bind_rows(session_integration)
train_data$feedback_type <- factor(train_data$feedback_type, 
                                   levels = c(-1, 1), 
                                   labels = c("Fail", "Success"))

train_data$feedback_type <- ifelse(train_data$feedback_type == "Fail", 0, 1)
set.seed(42)  # Ensure reproducibility
trainIndex <- createDataPartition(train_data$feedback_type, p = 0.8, list = FALSE)
train_data <- train_data[trainIndex, ]

train_matrix <- as.matrix(train_data[, c("contrast_left", "contrast_right", "spike_count")])

train_label <- train_data$feedback_type

dtrain <- xgb.DMatrix(data = train_matrix, label = train_label)

params <- list(
  objective = "binary:logistic",  # Binary classification
  eval_metric = "logloss",        # Log loss metric
  max_depth = 3,                  # Tree depth
  eta = 0.1,                      # Learning rate
  nrounds = 100                   # Number of boosting rounds
)
xgb_model <- xgboost(
  params = params,
  data = dtrain,
  nrounds = params$nrounds,
  verbose = 1
)

#4.4 Neural Network (NN) Model

library(tidyverse)
library(caret)
library(randomForest)
library(e1071)  # For SVM
library(xgboost)
library(tidyverse)
library(rpart)          # Decision Tree
library(dplyr)
library(DMwR2)

set.seed(123)  # Ensure reproducibility

# Combine them into training data
train_data <- bind_rows(session_integration)
train_data$feedback_type <- factor(train_data$feedback_type, 
                                   levels = c(-1, 1), 
                                   labels = c("Fail", "Success"))
library(nnet)
nn_model <- nnet(
  feedback_type ~ contrast_left + contrast_right + spike_count, 
  data = train_data,
  size = 5,   # Number of neurons in the hidden layer
  decay = 0.1, # Regularization parameter
  maxit = 200  # Maximum iterations
)
## # weights:  26
## initial  value 3245.510683 
## iter  10 value 3059.108911
## final  value 3059.107244 
## converged

The NN model converged successfully, meaning it found an optimal solution and small decrease in error (3062.98 → 3059.11), suggesting the model might be underfitting. In addition, there are 10 iterations were needed.

# Load the required library
library(pROC)
## Warning: 程序包'pROC'是用R版本4.4.3 来建造的
## Type 'citation("pROC")' for a citation.
## 
## 载入程序包：'pROC'
## The following objects are masked from 'package:stats':
## 
##     cov, smooth, var
min_length <- min(length(test_labels), length(test_pred_probs))
test_labels <- test_labels[1:min_length]
test_pred_probs <- test_pred_probs[1:min_length]
valid_indices <- complete.cases(test_labels, test_pred_probs)
test_labels <- test_labels[valid_indices]
test_pred_probs <- test_pred_probs[valid_indices]

roc_curve <- roc(test_labels, test_pred_probs)
## Setting levels: control = 0, case = 1
## Setting direction: controls < cases
auc_value <- auc(roc_curve)

# Plot the ROC curve
plot(roc_curve, col = "blue", main = "ROC Curve for XGBoost Model")

library(pROC)
roc_curve <- roc(test_label, test_pred_probs)
## Setting levels: control = 0, case = 1
## Setting direction: controls < cases

print(auc_value)
## Area under the curve: 0.6719

The Receiver Operating Characteristic (ROC) curve evaluates the classification model’s performance by plotting sensitivity (true positive rate) vs. specificity (false positive rate).The blue curve represents the performance of the XGBoost model, and the gray diagonal line represents random guessing (AUC = 0.5).The curve rises above the diagonal but does not reach close to the top-left corner, suggesting moderate performance—better than random guessing but not optimal.The Area Under the Curve (AUC) is in the range of 0.6-0.7, which indicating that it is a moderate model.

#Section 6 Discussion

Over multiple attempts, different machine learning models were tested to predict feedback type (Fail / Success). Each model has its strengths and weaknesses, with some performing better than others. Below is a summary of how each model performed and what can be done to improve them.

1.Decision Tree (CART) model The Decision Tree model achieved moderate accuracy but struggled with detecting “Fail” cases. It had a tendency to overfit to the training data, meaning it might not generalize well to unseen data. The model’s simplicity makes it easy to interpret, but it lacks the power of ensemble models. Strengths: Simple, interpretable, decent accuracy. Weaknesses: Overfitting risk, struggles with class imbalance. How to Improve: Tune the complexity parameter (cp), allow deeper trees, and consider ensemble methods like Random Forest.

  1. Random Forest model The Random Forest model performed slightly worse than the Decision Tree in terms of accuracy but provided a more stable and generalizable result. However, it still struggled with class imbalance, meaning it was much better at predicting “Success” than “Fail”. It had a moderate kappa score, indicating that it was only slightly better than random classification. Strengths: Handles non-linearity well, reduces overfitting. Weaknesses: Struggles with “Fail” cases, high false negatives. How to Improve: Balance the dataset using SMOTE, tune hyperparameters (mtry, ntree), and explore feature selection.

  2. Neural model The Neural Network model successfully trained but showed signs of underfitting, meaning it didn’t learn enough from the data. This likely happened because the input features were not properly scaled, and the model may have had too few neurons in the hidden layer. While neural networks are powerful for complex relationships, they require careful tuning. Strengths: Can model complex relationships if properly tuned. Weaknesses: Hard to interpret, prone to underfitting. How to Improve: Scale input features, increase the number of hidden neurons, and allow more training iterations (maxit).

4.XGBoost The XGBoost model was used to predict feedback type based on neural activity (spike trains) and stimulus contrasts. The performance was evaluated using the ROC Curve, which provides insights into the model’s ability to distinguish between the two classes (“Fail” and “Success”).For the predictive power, the AUC (Area Under the Curve) value (estimated to be between 0.6 and 0.7) suggests moderate discrimination ability and the log loss ranged between 0.547 and 0.673, indicating that the model makes reasonable but not highly confident predictions.
